### WORK.md (current state)
Let's design a skill tree type system. The characters themselves are just people with gender, histories, names, flavor (history, favorite sayings, origins, ethnicities, etc).
  Characters grow in different directions. Like in many games, their stats dictate what they'd be best at. Someone who is smart can be a hacker. Someone who is strong can be a bruiser.
  Someone with charisma can be a charmer, etc
  The game has a giant set of "class names" and it comes up with the appropriate class name for you based on your skill set. It will approximately give you the label is thinks best fits. This functionally does nothing, but is a fun flavor mechanic.
  Based on the skill list and possible combos of skills, consider ~500 "class names" we could apply. In-game, as characters grow and their skill sets change, always re-check for the most appropriate class name and apply it in the character profile.
  The skill tree system is like any other such tree (ie, tech tree in Civilization). Think of like 300 different skills; start by looking at the classes in the current system; each class should be a skill that can be learned. Each skill can also be leveled up. Make three levels of each skill.
  Leveling up the skill improves how well they do it (hacker hacks faster, bruiser does more damage, charmer has a better success rate, sneaker sneaks by more efficiently.) Generally, push the skill to be faster / bigger numbers.
  As a person uses a specific skill, they gain experience; enough experience and they can learn the skills in the skill tree that require mastery of dependency skills OR they can level up the skill they're using.
  Each character, when generated has 3 skills; since certain skills in the skill tree can only be reached by mastery of previous skills, this locks characters into archetypes depending on the skills they start with (since there's no way to learn the base skill you didn't start with)
  Some (many?) skills in the skill tree have multiple dependencies that must exist before they can be learned.
  Ask me any questions you have and I'll clarify everything.
Often when I walk into a guard's view, I don't get caught. I should certainly be seen if I cross through the guards flashlight area, or walk right in front of them in well lit areas. Same with the camera. If a character is "staring forward", then they should see on both sides, though they'll have a limited range. Fix this. They still often don't see me when I walk right into their line of site. They see me when they suddenly turn towards me and I'm in the line of site. I want them to detect me when I walk directly towards them.
